      <div class="faq-section">
        <div class="section-eyebrow">FAQ</div>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">What is the tax rate on bonuses in 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Bonuses are taxed as ordinary income at your marginal federal tax rate in 2026. Employers withhold at the IRS supplemental rate of 22% for bonuses under $1 million and 37% for amounts above $1 million. Your actual tax rate depends on your total annual income and filing status.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Why does my bonus look so heavily taxed?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Two reasons. First, the 22% flat withholding is higher than the marginal rate for many workers in lower brackets &mdash; but you get that over-withholding back as a refund. Second, if your employer uses the aggregate method, withholding can be even higher temporarily because it treats the bonus as if you earn that amount every pay period. Your final tax is settled when you file.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Does FICA apply to bonuses in 2026?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Bonuses are subject to Social Security (6.2%) and Medicare (1.45%) withholding in addition to income tax withholding, as long as you have not already exceeded the Social Security wage base (~$180,400 projected for 2026). If you have hit the SS wage base by the time you receive your bonus, Social Security will not be withheld but Medicare still will.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Can I contribute my bonus directly to my 401(k)?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">Most 401(k) plans allow bonus contributions, but it depends on your plan document. Check with HR before the bonus is paid. Many plans require an advance election change, and some only allow standard payroll deferral percentages. If you can contribute, it reduces your taxable income for the year.</div>
          </div>
                    <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false">Is a year-end bonus taxed differently than a mid-year bonus?<span class="faq-chevron"><svg width="12" height="12" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-answer">No. The tax rate is the same regardless of when in the year the bonus is paid. Withholding may differ slightly depending on the aggregate method calculation, but your total annual income determines your final tax. The only timing consideration is whether pushing income into a new calendar year affects your tax bracket, which only matters if the bonus spans December/January.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

